TY  - JOUR
AU  - Yu, Zhihao
T1  - Environmental Protection: A Theory of Direct and Indirect Competition for Political Influence
PY  - 2005
Y1  - 2005/01/01
DO  - 10.1111/0034-6527.00332
JO  - The Review of Economic Studies
JA  - Rev Econ Stud
VL  - 72
IS  - 1
SP  - 269
EP  - 286
SN  - 0034-6527
AB  - How is it that environmental groups can have a strong impact on environmental policy but without much lobbying? This paper develops a model of “direct” (lobbying the government) and “indirect” (persuading the public) competition for political influence and finds that they are complementary. However, an increase in the effectiveness of public persuasion, or a rise of public environmental awareness, induces substitution between the two. The findings establish that the empirical phenomenon of lack of political contribution from environmental groups may not be related to financial constraints, but to their greater effectiveness in public persuasion and growing public environmental awareness.
Y2  - 3/25/2024
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/0034-6527.00332
ER  - 



